President Bush underwent a colonoscopy procedure on Saturday at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Maryland. Prosecutors have asked for permission to euthanize the dogs involved in the case, but the dogs could serve as important evidence in the cases against Vick and his admitted co-conspirators. A Sudanese court has found a British teacher, Gillian Gibbons, guilty of insulting religion after she allowed her students to name a teddy bear "Mohammed." Gibbons was sentenced to 15 days in prison and faces deportation after her sentence is served. The teacher was arrested on Sunday and faced charges under Article 125 of Sudan's constitution, which relates to insulting religion and inciting hatred. The British Foreign Office has expressed its dissatisfaction with the verdict and is providing consular assistance to Gibbons. The teacher's school, Unity High School, has refused to comment on the situation.

Seven college students died in a weekend fire at a beach house in Ocean Isle Beach, North Carolina. The fire occurred early Sunday morning and engulfed the house in flames, leaving little more than the framing intact. The victims were identified as six University of South Carolina students and a Clemson University student. Six other South Carolina students were able to escape the house in time, but one of them, Chip Auman's 18-year-old daughter, was hospitalized due to smoke inhalation. The cause of the fire is still under investigation, but authorities do not believe foul play was involved. The university community is offering support and counseling to students affected by the tragedy.

Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez has cut all ties with Colombia as long as current Colombian President Alvaro Uribe is in office. Chavez had been mediating efforts to secure the release of hostages held by the FARC and ELN, but Uribe ended Chavez's participation without notice, citing protocol. Chavez accused Uribe of lying and bowing to pressure from Washington to "get rid of Chavez." Despite this, Chavez expressed his willingness to help the Colombian people.

Ann Curley is a type I diabetic who has been managing her disease for 40 years. She was diagnosed at the age of 7 by Dr. Robert Deputy, who told her parents that she would only live to the age of 20 or 30. Despite this grim prognosis, Curley has been able to manage her diabetes through self-sufficiency and the advancement of technology. She has used insulin pumps, continuous glucose monitors, and blood sugar testing to keep her blood sugar levels under control. Curley is hopeful about the future of diabetes management and is aiming to live for another 40 years.

Former Wales and British Lions center Ray Gravell has passed away at the age of 56 due to a suspected heart attack. Gravell won 23 caps for Wales and played on the Lions tour of South Africa in 1980. He was a dominant player in his time and was known for his passion, flair, and dignity on the field. After retiring as a player in 1985, Gravell became president of Llanelli RFC and the Llanelli Scarlets, and also pursued a career as an actor and rugby broadcaster. Earlier this year, Gravell had his right leg amputated below the knee due to complications linked with his diabetes, but he had been recovering well. The Welsh Rugby Union (WRU) has praised Gravell as an ambassador for rugby and Wales, and a great example of how the game can bring out the best in a person.

Senator Barack Obama's presidential campaign is facing controversy after it was revealed that one of the performers at an upcoming gospel concert in South Carolina, Donnie McClurkin, has made statements against the LGBTQ+ community. McClurkin has said that homosexuality is a choice and that he was able to overcome it through prayer. This has sparked outrage among gay and lesbian leaders, who are calling for Obama to remove McClurkin from the concert bill. Obama has issued a statement saying that he strongly disagrees with McClurkin's views and will continue to fight for LGBTQ+ rights as president. The controversy has raised questions about Obama's ability to unite disparate voting blocs under his umbrella of "change."

Atletico Madrid defeated Real Zaragoza 4-0 in the Spanish Primera Liga, with Luis Garcia scoring his first goal for the club and Maxi Rodriguez and Diego Forlan also finding the net. Atletico moved up to sixth place in the table, while Zaragoza remained in 14th. In other matches, Getafe recorded their first win of the season with a 2-0 victory over Murcia, and Valladolid suffered a 2-1 defeat against Athletic Bilbao.

Las Vegas Sands Corp. is a company that owns and operates several casino resorts, including The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino and the Sands Expo and Convention Center in Las Vegas, Nevada, as well as the Sands Macau in Macau, China. The company has received recognition for revolutionizing the Las Vegas hotel industry and has been honored with various awards for its properties. In 2004, the company went public with an initial public offering (IPO) that was highly successful, with the stock price rising 61% on its opening day. The Venetian Casino Resort is one of the most productive properties on the Las Vegas Strip, with an occupancy rate of 98.3% and an average daily room rate of $219 during the nine months ended September 30, 2004.

U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice has announced that State Department officials may be directed to serve in war-torn Iraq, despite objections from foreign service officers. Rice stated that "people need to serve where they are needed" and that the State Department will fill new positions in Iraq with volunteers or through directed assignments if necessary. However, some foreign service officers have expressed concerns about the safety of serving in Iraq, with one calling the order to serve there a "potential death sentence." The State Department has already notified about 200 people considered prime candidates for the positions, and those who decline could face dismissal. Rice emphasized that the State Department is doing everything it can to protect its diplomats, but also stressed the importance of meeting U.S. obligations in Iraq.

A series of wildfires in Southern California have caused widespread destruction and loss of life, with the death toll rising to seven as of Thursday. Four bodies were found in a canyon in the path of the blaze, and the number of deaths attributed directly to the fires grew to seven after the charred bodies of four people believed to be illegal immigrants were found in a canyon east of San Diego. Seven other deaths are labeled as fire-related, including three elderly people who died during evacuations and four others who died after being evacuated. Improving weather conditions allowed more people to return home Thursday, but new evacuations were ordered in areas where the unrelenting flames marched on. The cost of homes destroyed by the wildfires is likely to top $1 billion in San Diego County alone, and federal help is available for those affected by the fires. Almost 9,000 firefighters are battling the blazes, augmented by reinforcements from dozens of states across the country. The fires have scorched 472,478 acres (738 square miles), an area roughly three-quarters of the size of Rhode Island, and have destroyed roughly one-third of San Diego County's lucrative avocado crop, along with other croplands, greenhouses and nurseries.

The commander of the USS Hampton, Cmdr. Michael B. Portland, has been relieved of his command due to a loss of confidence in his ability to lead the crew. This decision comes after an investigation into misconduct by crew members, including falsifying inspection records for the cooling system of the ship's nuclear reactor. Six personnel have been punished for their actions, and one officer and two enlisted crew members have been temporarily reassigned to Submarine Squadron 11. The misconduct was discovered on September 17, and a fact-finding investigation is ongoing. The USS Hampton remains in port in San Diego, California, with a crew of 13 officers and 116 enlisted personnel.

A bus crashed into a pickup truck and an 18-wheeler on a highway in Arkansas, killing the pickup driver and two bus riders. Forty people were injured in the crash, which shut down a 13-mile stretch of Interstate-40. The bus was traveling from Chicago to Dallas when the accident occurred. The driver of the bus and the driver of the 18-wheeler suffered minor injuries, while two passengers were found dead inside the bus. The names of the deceased have not been released.

Kelly Pless, a 31-year-old graduate student from Sunny Isles Beach, Florida, struggled with her weight throughout her adult life, reaching a peak of 220 pounds. Despite her doubts and fears, she decided to make a change and started walking and running to lose weight. Over the next three to four months, she lost 95 pounds and kept it off for 1½ years. Pless adopted an "eat to live" philosophy and focused on portion control, satisfying her cravings for sweets with fruit. She also pays close attention to societal pressure and restaurant portion sizes. Through her weight loss journey, Pless has become healthier and more confident, and has set a new professional goal to pursue a doctorate in food and exercise psychology to help others battling obesity and eating disorders.

The Singapore Airlines A380, the world's largest commercial jet, made its maiden passenger journey between Singapore and Sydney this week, two years late and billions of dollars over budget. The aircraft features "beyond first class" cabins with private suites, double beds, and in-flight entertainment systems. The airline has ordered 19 superjumbos and will begin scheduled service between Singapore and Sydney next month, with plans to expand to London's Heathrow Airport in 2008. The A380's delivery schedule is expected to be challenging, with 185 orders from 15 customers, including Emirates, Qantas, and Singapore Airlines. The aircraft's key features include a wingspan of 79.8 meters, length of 73 meters, and internal cabin width of 6.58 meters. The A380's flight range is 15,000 kilometers, and it can carry 555 passengers, compared to the 416 passengers that the Boeing 747 can carry. The airline has received high demand for tickets, with the top ticket price selling for US$100,380, and the cheapest ticket selling for US$560.

The illegal export of US military technology to Iran and China poses a growing threat, according to the Justice Department. The department plans to tighten monitoring of export licenses and increase export restrictions on technologies that could have both civilian and military applications and could pose a danger to US national security in the hands of terrorists or potential enemies. The department highlighted two recent cases, including a Pittsburgh company sentenced for lying about an illegal export of products that can be used in nuclear reactions and in the nose cones of ballistic missiles, and two men charged last week with attempting to illegally export restricted components for F-4 and F-14 fighter jets, with F-14 components highly sought after by Iran.

The article discusses the visit of King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia to London and the strong trading and business relationship between the two countries. Saudi Arabia is the UK's largest trading partner in the Middle East and the UK is the second largest foreign investor in the Kingdom. The article highlights the significant increase in UK exports to Saudi Arabia, particularly in the non-oil sector, and the numerous joint ventures between the two countries. It also mentions the recent deal worth over $10 billion for the purchase of Eurofighter Typhoon Jets by the Kingdom and the UK government's decision to call off a Serious Fraud Office investigation into defense contracts with Saudi Arabia. The article concludes that despite any political sensitivity surrounding the visit, the relationship between the two nations is far deeper and the opportunities for businessmen are immense.

Tens of thousands of Congolese refugees fled camps in the Democratic Republic of Congo as rebel troops attacked government forces in the area. The UNHCR reported that about 28,000 refugees abandoned the first three camps, while about 2,000 left a fourth camp. The agency identified the affected camps as Mugunga I, Mugunga II, Lac Vert and Bulengo. The UNHCR stated that 375,000 Congolese in North Kivu province have been forced from their homes in the past year, with 160,000 fleeing their homes in the past two months amid ongoing fighting between renegade troops and government forces.

Genarlow Wilson, a 21-year-old man who was released from prison last week after serving two years of a 10-year sentence for aggravated child molestation, has revealed that he rejected a plea deal from prosecutors because he did not want to be labeled a sex offender. Despite the deal potentially releasing him from prison months earlier, Wilson felt that the label would have a significant impact on his future and he did not want to have to register as a sex offender for the rest of his life. He is now focused on his future and hopes to major in sociology in college, and is determined to be more conservative, more alert, and more appreciative of the blessings in his life.

The confirmation of Michael Mukasey as Attorney General is likely, despite opposition from some Democratic senators due to his views on waterboarding and the president's power to order electronic surveillance. Two key Democratic senators, Dianne Feinstein and Charles Schumer, have announced their support for Mukasey's nomination, while Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy has announced he will vote against it. Leahy and other Democrats have expressed concerns about Mukasey's views on torture and the separation of powers, while Feinstein and Schumer argue that Mukasey is the best available candidate and that voting him down would only perpetuate acting and recess appointments. Despite these concerns, President Bush has demanded the Senate confirm Mukasey, citing the need for a full national security team in place during a time of war.

Nine people were killed and 19 injured when a tour bus carrying people on a ski trip rolled over on a highway in southeastern Utah. The bus, operated by Arrow Stage Lines, was traveling from Telluride, Colorado to Phoenix, Arizona when it left the right side of the highway and rolled over several times, tumbling 41 feet down an embankment. The crash occurred at around 7:30 pm on Sunday, and rescue crews from multiple states responded to the scene. The Utah Highway Patrol reported that the road was wet but not icy at the time of the crash. The cause of the accident is still under investigation.

Banksy is a British street artist known for his subversive and satirical public art. He has gained international recognition for his stencil works that often depict political and social commentary. Despite his popularity and high-profile sales, his identity remains a mystery. Banksy's work has been embraced by the art world, with major galleries selling his pieces for millions of dollars. However, local authorities have not always been supportive of his work, with some pledging to remove his graffiti from their streets. His latest piece in East London has sparked speculation about his identity, with a passer-by claiming to have taken a photo of the artist at work.

The article discusses the ongoing garbage crisis in Naples, Italy, which has been plagued by mismanagement, political interference, and mafia profiteering for decades. Despite the appointment of eight different commissioners, the problem has yet to be solved, and millions of euros in emergency funds have been wasted. The local mafia, known as the Camorra, is allegedly taking advantage of the situation by disposing of waste in the open or at overflowing dumps, and has burrowed its way so deeply into the system that every attempt to fix the problem has proved futile. The government has now proposed re-opening a previously shut dump to dispose of 3,700 tons of waste that is laying in the streets of Naples and surrounding areas, but this has sparked protests from residents who were promised that a golf course would be built on the site instead.

President Vladimir Putin has announced that Russia will resume regular flights of its strategic bombers beyond its borders, citing security threats as the reason. 14 strategic bombers took off simultaneously from 7 airfields across Russia early on Friday and will conduct long-range missions on a regular basis. Putin stated that Russia's decision to restore flights by its strategic aviation is a response to the changing security situation and the lack of reciprocity from other countries. The move is likely to add to Western concerns about Russia's growing assertiveness, with some drawing parallels to the Cold War era.

This article from Mental Floss highlights 9 iconic American foods and their origins. Here's a summary of each one:

1. The Hamburger - Louis' Lunch in New Haven, Connecticut, is credited with inventing the hamburger in 1900. The restaurant still serves the same basic menu today, with no ketchup allowed.
2. The Fried Twinkie - ChipShop in Brooklyn, New York, took the Twinkie to new heights by deep-frying it. The owner, Christopher Sell, was trained in classical French cuisine and wanted to create something innovative.
3. Root Beer Float - In 1893, a failed gold miner in Colorado, Frank J. Wisner, created the root beer float by floating a scoop of vanilla ice cream in a glass of his Myers Avenue Red root beer.
4. Corn Dogs - Ed Waldmire Jr. invented the corn dog in 1946 in Springfield, Illinois. He called it the "Cozy Dog," and the first corn dog on a stick was served at the Cozy Dog Drive In.
5. The Pizzeria - Gennaro Lombardi opened the first pizzeria in New York City in 1905. His employee, Anthony "Totonno" Pero, started selling pizzas out of the back of the store, and the establishment was later licensed as a pizzeria.
6. Fat Darrell - R.U. Hungry in New Brunswick, New Jersey, created the Fat Darrell sandwich in 1997. It contains chicken fingers, mozzarella sticks, French fries, and marinara sauce on a sandwich.
7. Philly Cheesesteak - Pat's King of Steaks in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, is credited with inventing the Philly cheesesteak in 1932. The sandwich was created by hot dog stand owners Pasquale and Harry Olivieri, who added onions to their steak sandwiches.
8. Onion Rings - The Pig Stand in Dallas, Texas, is said to have invented the onion ring in the mid-1950s. The recipe is jealously guarded by the Kern family, who copyrighted the name and only serve real "Derby-Pie®" through their company, Kern's Kitchen, Inc.

Each of these foods has a unique origin story, and they have become staples of American cuisine.

Authorities in Azerbaijan have uncovered a terror plot against the US Embassy in Baku, prompting the facility to close to the public. The plot was unraveled after a weekend raid outside Baku that netted several suspected members of a radical Islamic group. The group had planned to attack the embassy and government buildings, but no specific individuals were targeted. The US State Department has issued a warden message warning Americans in Azerbaijan to take precautions, and US authorities are working closely with their counterparts in Baku to determine when normal embassy operations will resume.

A North Korean freighter was hijacked by pirates off the coast of Somalia, but the crew was able to regain control of the ship after a deadly battle. The USS James E. Williams, a US Navy destroyer, responded to reports of the hijacking and ordered the pirates to give up their weapons. When the crew of the Dai Hong Dan stormed the bridge, a fierce battle ensued, resulting in the deaths of two pirates and the injury of three crew members. The remaining pirates were captured and are being held aboard the North Korean vessel. This is the second incident of piracy reported in recent days, with a second US Navy destroyer searching for pirates who hijacked a Japanese-owned ship. The US and North Korea have no diplomatic relations, and the incident highlights the ongoing problem of piracy in the region.

Debra Lafave, a former Florida middle school teacher convicted of having sex with a student, violated her probation by hugging a young co-worker. Lafave was arrested after talking with a teenager and is not allowed to have contact with anyone under 18. A judge found that the violation was "not willful and substantial" and did not send Lafave to jail. Lafave acknowledged that she was aware that hugs and other forms of physical contact with minors violated the terms of her probation. She denied talking about her sex life with co-workers but admitted that her co-workers spoke freely about sex in a "small group setting." Lafave explained that the hug she gave to the young co-worker was out of her good nature and came in a casual atmosphere of a small restaurant where co-workers felt like family.

Ralph Lauren is a fashion designer who has been in the industry for 40 years and has had a significant impact on the way people dress and live. He is known for his classic, luxurious designs and his ability to create a consistent image across his brand. Lauren believes that the key to longevity in the fashion industry is to keep doing what you do best and to get your message out to the consumer. He has a global reach and has expanded his brand to include stores in many countries, including China and Japan. Lauren is confident that there is still room for growth and expansion, despite the fast-paced and ever-changing nature of the fashion industry.

A suspect in the fatal shooting of a Philadelphia police officer has been captured in Miami, Florida. John Lewis, 27, was taken into custody without incident at a homeless shelter where he was found praying with a Bible. Lewis is suspected of shooting Officer Chuck Cassidy on October 31, who died the next day. Investigators say Lewis was spotted on security video boarding a bus to Miami on Saturday night. Former co-workers of Lewis are surprised by the allegations against him, describing him as "nice." Lewis has a history of drug arrests, with cases still pending.

The article provides a list of five cars that are stylish and affordable for first-time buyers, with a price range of around $20,000. The cars are:

1. Hyundai Tiburon - a sporty coupe with a touch of Italian styling and a powerful engine that can accelerate from 0-60 mph in under six seconds.
2. Mazda MazdaSpeed3 - a pocket rocket that can hit 155 mph and has a secret to its performance: torque negation in the low gears.
3. Pontiac G5 GT Coupe - a more affordable version of the Chevy Cobalt SS, with a less horizontal grille and more sculpted valance. It has a 2.4-liter 173-hp engine that can accelerate from 0-60 mph in 7.5 seconds.
4. Ford Mustang V6 - a revamped chassis that makes the Mustang an outstanding product at a price that's hard to beat. It has a 210-hp V6 engine that performs admirably and emits a low-down growl.
5. Honda Fit - a compact car that is energetic, filled with flair, and boasts a vertical fold in the bonnet. It is colossally roomy inside and has great gas mileage.

The article also mentions the Scion xB and Civic Coupe as other notable options.

President Bush criticized the Democratic-controlled Congress on Tuesday, accusing them of not getting their work done and wasting time on investigations and failed votes to pull troops out of Iraq. He also vetoed a children's health insurance bill, which Democrats are trying to pass again. Bush threatened to veto a "three-bill pileup" and urged Congress to pass each bill one at a time in a fiscally responsible manner. Democrats fired back, saying that Bush's comments on appropriations bills and fiscal responsibility "ring hollow" and that they are the party of fiscal responsibility. The Senate could vote on the children's health bill as early as Tuesday.

Lee Boyd Malvo, the sniper who terrorized the Washington area in 2002, is still grappling with shame, guilt, and remorse according to a letter he wrote to CNN. Malvo is serving a life sentence at Virginia's toughest prison and has spent hundreds of hours with a social worker named Carmeta Albarus-Lindo, who has helped him deal with his emotional trauma. Albarus-Lindo has revealed that Malvo was brainwashed by his surrogate father, John Allen Muhammad, who convinced him that violence was the only way to correct perceived injustices to African-Americans. Despite the jury's decision to spare Malvo's life, some investigators were horrified and the victims' families are content with the verdict. Malvo will never forgive himself for what happened and has taken up drawing as a way to cope with his emotions. Muhammad, who is also serving a life sentence, wants to correct inaccurate statements made by the media about his relationship with Malvo.

Here is a summary of the article:

Italy national coach Roberto Donadoni has named a 23-man squad for next Saturday's Euro 2008 qualifier against Scotland, including striker Cristiano Lucarelli who scored twice against South Africa. Donadoni has left out veteran forwards Filippo Inzaghi and Alessandro Del Piero, but has handed Juventus striker Raffaele Palladino his first call-up to the senior squad. The squad also includes the return of captain Fabio Cannavaro from suspension. Italy are currently third in Group B, two points behind leaders France and one point below Scotland.

Erik Prince, the CEO and chairman of Blackwater USA, appeared before the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform to address an FBI investigation into a September 16 shootout involving Blackwater personnel in Iraq that resulted in the deaths of Iraqi civilians. Prince stated that Blackwater is a company of dedicated professionals who provide training to the military and law enforcement communities and risk their lives to protect Americans overseas. He emphasized that Blackwater personnel are all military and law enforcement veterans and that the company shares the committee's interest in ensuring accountability and oversight of contract personnel supporting U.S. operations. Prince also provided information on the company's operations in Iraq, including that Blackwater reports to the embassy's regional security officer and that the company does not engage in offensive or military missions but performs only defensive security functions. He concluded by stating that he believes Blackwater acted appropriately in the September 16 incident and is willing to answer the committee's questions.

UEFA has banned Benfica midfielder Augustin Binya for six matches following his dangerous tackle on Celtic's Scott Brown in their Champions League match last week. Binya was sent off for the challenge, which injured Brown but did not break his leg. Binya apologized for the tackle, but UEFA's control and disciplinary body ruled that it was one of the worst they had ever seen and posed a serious risk to Brown's physical health. The ban will keep Binya out of Benfica's remaining Group D matches and any potential knockout stage matches in the Champions League or UEFA Cup. It will also carry over to future seasons if Benfica finishes bottom of the group and is eliminated from Europe.

In a recent CNN/Opinion Research Corporation poll, Sen. Hillary Clinton (D-NY) remains the front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination, with 44% of likely Democratic voters supporting her. Clinton's closest rival, Sen. Barack Obama (D-IL), received 25% of the vote. Former Sen. John Edwards (D-NC) came in third with 14%. The poll also found that Clinton's support has slipped slightly since last month, but she still holds a significant lead over her rivals. In the Republican race, former New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani remains the front-runner, with 28% of the vote. Former Sen. Fred Thompson (R-TN) came in second with 19%. The poll also found that Clinton would lead Giuliani in a head-to-head matchup, 51% to 45%. The poll involved 467 interviews conducted on November 2-4 with Democrats or independents who lean Democratic, and 397 interviews with Republicans or independents who lean Republican.

Russian President Vladimir Putin visited Tehran, Iran on Tuesday, where he met with Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad and other leaders of Caspian Sea nations. Putin stated that Iran should be allowed to pursue its nuclear program for peaceful purposes, and that Russia is cooperating with Iranian nuclear agencies to achieve this goal. He also emphasized that no Caspian nation should offer its territory to third parties for military action against other Caspian states. Putin's visit is the first by a Kremlin leader to Iran since 1943, and is seen as a show of Russia's independence in global affairs.

Three French journalists were released from custody in Chad after being charged with complicity in an alleged plot to kidnap African children for adoption in Europe. The journalists were among seven Europeans released by a Chadian judge, along with a Spanish flight crew. The remaining six French nationals from the charity Zoe's Ark, as well as four Chadians and four members of the flight crew, remain in custody facing serious charges. The children involved in the alleged plot may never return to their families due to the difficulty in determining their backgrounds, according to the Red Cross. French President Nicolas Sarkozy expressed satisfaction with the release of the Europeans, but emphasized the importance of respecting Chad's sovereignty. The scandal is not expected to affect the strong relations between France and Chad or the planned deployment of a European force to protect refugees in the region.

A Black Hawk helicopter carrying 11 US military personnel crashed in northeastern Italy, killing 4 people and injuring 7, including 2 who later died. The helicopter, attached to the 1st Battalion, 214th Aviation Regiment, crashed near the Piave River north of Treviso, between the towns of Maserata Sul Piave and Santa Lucia Di Piave. The US military is not releasing the names of the victims, pending notification of their families. The cause of the crash is under investigation.

Three men have been arrested and charged with murder in the shooting death of a University of Memphis football player, Taylor Bradford. The men, DeeShawn Tate, Victor Trezevant, and Courtney Washington, were charged with murder in perpetration of attempted aggravated robbery. According to Memphis Police Department Director Larry Godwin, the three men were arrested with the help of a citizen's tip and Crimestoppers, and the investigation is ongoing. Godwin stated that Bradford was targeted because of information that was believed to be in his possession, and that none of the arrested suspects were students at the university. Shelby County District Attorney General William L. Gibbons said that prosecutors are considering seeking the death penalty in the case, but no decision has been made. Bradford, a popular and well-liked student, was a marketing major who was 36 credit hours short of graduation.

A court has ordered Britney Spears to give up custody of her two children to her ex-husband, Kevin Federline, effective Wednesday at noon. Federline will retain custody of the children "until further order of the court." The decision comes after Spears failed a drug test and made derogatory remarks about Federline and his family. The court also ordered Spears to spend eight hours per week working with a "parenting coach" and to avoid alcohol and drugs when taking custody of the children. This development comes amid a career slump for Spears, who is set to release a new album on November 13.

Former football star O.J. Simpson was released from jail on Wednesday after posting $250,000 bail. Simpson had been in jail since January 11 after prosecutors alleged he violated the terms of his bail by attempting to contact a co-defendant. At a hearing on Wednesday, a judge doubled Simpson's bail to ensure his appearance at an April 7 trial and scolded him for not taking the matter seriously. Simpson posted bail at about 6:15 pm local time and was released from jail. The judge also imposed strict conditions on Simpson's release, including no contact with victims, witnesses, or co-defendants, and no phone messages to third parties. Simpson faces trial on 12 criminal counts, including conspiracy, kidnapping, robbery, burglary, coercion, and assault with a deadly weapon.

The US Air Force has recalled F-15E Strike Eagle jets to service in Iraq and Afghanistan after grounding other F-15 models following a crash in Missouri. The recall includes a one-time inspection of critical parts on the airframe, including hydraulic system lines, longerons, and skin panels. The investigation into the crash is ongoing, and the Air Force has not released details on the cause of the incident. The F-15E is the youngest and most sophisticated model in the F-15 inventory and is heavily used by Central Command for ground support in the U.S.-led wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.

Former detainees of Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) have accused the agency of forcibly injecting them with psychotropic drugs while trying to deport them. Two immigrants, Raymond Soeoth and Amadou Diouf, are plaintiffs in a class-action lawsuit brought by the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) against the government. They claim they were injected with drugs against their will, including the powerful anti-psychotic drug Haldol, which is often used to treat schizophrenia or other mental illnesses. The allegations were raised by Sen. Joe Lieberman and responded to by ICE, which stated that no detainee should be "involuntarily medicated without a court order," except in emergency situations. However, both Soeoth and Diouf deny exhibiting any combative behavior before being injected with the drugs. The case is ongoing, and if the plaintiffs lose, they may be deported again.

A 3-year-old girl was videotaped being sexually assaulted by a baby sitter while her mother was at work. The mother only found out about the abuse when a family friend called her and told her to watch the news. The mother's attorney, Jerry T. Donohue, said that the abuse occurred before the girl was 3 years old and that the mother is cooperating with investigators. The suspect, Chester Arthur Stiles, 37, is being sought by the FBI and has a previous record of sexual assault and lewdness with a minor. The mother has asked the media to leave the family alone and has not watched the videotape. The FBI is also investigating Stiles in a separate matter involving state charges of sexual assault and lewdness with a minor under the age of 14.

Senator Barack Obama criticized his Democratic presidential rival, Senator Hillary Clinton, for voting to declare Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps a foreign terrorist group, saying it was a "blank check" for President Bush to take military action against Iran. Obama argued that Clinton's vote showed flawed judgment, as she had also supported the resolution to authorize force in Ira in 2002. Clinton defended her vote, saying it was a nonbinding resolution and that sanctions would be imposed to send a message to Iran's leadership. Obama also criticized Clinton's judgment on the Iraq war and suggested he could better unite the country and offer "something new" as a presidential candidate.

Charges against Bryant Purvis, one of the six black students accused of beating a white student in Jena, Louisiana, were reduced to second-degree aggravated battery during his arraignment. Purvis entered a not guilty plea to the reduced charges and is focusing on his studies and basketball. Charges have been reduced against at least five of the students in the racially charged "Jena 6" case, with the exception of Mychal Bell, who is still in jail due to a probation violation.

Up to 1,000 human rights campaigners demonstrated in front of No. 10 Downing Street in London, calling on the British government to demand that full democracy be restored in Pakistan. The protesters carried placards and chanted in support of the resignation of Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf, who imposed a state of emergency in the country last week. Rapper T.I. was arrested in Atlanta on Saturday on federal gun charges after his bodyguard-turned-informant delivered three machine guns and two silencers to the hip-hop star, according to the Justice Department. T.I., whose real name is Clifford Harris, was taken into custody without incident and is expected to appear in court on Friday for a bond hearing. The 27-year-old entertainer was convicted on felony drug charges in 1998 and is not allowed to own guns due to his criminal record. Authorities found six other guns, five of them loaded, in his bedroom closet during a search of his home. The arrest came after the bodyguard, who has worked for Harris since July, was arrested purchasing the machine guns and silencers from an undercover ATF agent. The bodyguard then agreed to cooperate with the ATF and made phone calls to Harris, which were recorded. Harris was supposed to meet the bodyguard in a shopping center parking lot to pick up the guns, and he was arrested there without incident. The rapper's music is built around the drug culture and he has additional arrests and probation violations for unlawfully possessing firearms, according to court documents.

Three Chinese nationals have been arrested in the United States for importing and selling counterfeit luxury handbags and wallets worth millions of dollars. The operation is believed to be one of the largest counterfeit schemes ever discovered, with over 300,000 fake items bearing the names of brands such as Burberry, Gucci, and Coach. The alleged leaders of the operation are three Chinese citizens living in New York, who were arrested after a five-year investigation by Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents. The charges were unsealed after the defendants were taken into custody, and authorities seized and froze 29 bank accounts and three properties in New York. The defendants will be arraigned in Richmond, Virginia at a later date.

Bill Proenza, the director of the National Hurricane Center (NHC), has left his position after nearly half of the center's staff signed a petition calling for his ouster. Proenza is still employed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), but he is currently on leave. The petition was signed by 23 staff members, including four of five senior hurricane specialists, who were unhappy with Proenza's comments about a key hurricane satellite called QuikSCAT, as well as the overall environment at the center. Proenza told CNN he had contacted his superiors in Washington about "ways to move forward," but he did not think the staff should dictate leadership through petitions. Proenza graduated from Florida State University with a degree in meteorology and began his career in tropical meteorology in the mid-1960s at NHC.

At least 1,723 people have died and 15,000 have been injured in Bangladesh after a devastating tropical cyclone, Cyclone Sidr, ripped through the western coast of the country. The cyclone made landfall Thursday night and unleashed floodwaters, causing widespread destruction and displacement. The government has identified the 12 worst-affected districts, all located on the southern coast, and the Bangladeshi air force, army, and navy are working to provide shelter for the many people who have been displaced. Power is still out in much of the country, but it is being restored. The U.N. World Food Programme has enough high-energy biscuits to feed 400,000 people for several days, and other humanitarian groups, such as Save the Children, are appealing for aid to assist children and families affected by the disaster. The US Department of State has pledged to work with the government and foreign donors to assist in relieving the effects of the disaster.

A man has been indicted on federal charges for allegedly displaying hangman's nooses from the back of a pickup truck during a civil rights march in Jena, Louisiana. The man, Jeremiah Munsen, 18, of Grant Parish, repeatedly drove slowly past a group of marchers gathered at a bus depot in Alexandria, as they awaited buses to return them to Tennessee. Authorities say he and an unnamed conspirator attached nooses to their pickup on September 20 and drove to Alexandria to threaten and intimidate the marchers. A juvenile passenger was apprehended with Munsen and admitted to tying the nooses and having "KKK" tattooed on his chest. The indictment accuses Munsen of a federal civil rights conspiracy violation and a federal hate crime.

R.E.M. debuted a new song, "Until the Day Is Done," on CNN's "Anderson Cooper 360°" program as part of the network's four-hour documentary "Planet in Peril." The song will also appear in the documentary, which focuses on environmental crises around the world. R.E.M. singer Michael Stipe said the band was honored to be involved with the project and that the group's longstanding commitment to environmental causes made them a natural choice. The documentary features CNN anchor Anderson Cooper, chief medical correspondent Dr. Sanjay Gupta, and "Animal Planet" host and wildlife biologist Jeff Corwin, and was filmed in 13 countries. "Planet in Peril" will air on October 23 and 24 at 9 p.m. ET on CNN.

A U.S. government plan to build a border fence along the Texas-Mexico border is facing opposition from about 100 landowners, including Eloisa Tamez, who owns three acres of land along the border. Tamez is determined to fight the government's efforts, saying she will not allow them to survey her land. The government believes the fence will help curb illegal immigration and drug trafficking, but opponents argue it is a waste of resources and will not be effective. The government has begun legal action against landowners and municipalities who have refused to give surveyors access to their land, and the Department of Homeland Security has rejected requests for further consultations with opponents of the fence.

The article discusses how some Christian pastors in urban areas are turning to the Church of Scientology for help with social programs, despite the church's controversial reputation. The pastors, including Rev. Charles Kennedy of the Glorious Church of God in Christ in Tampa, Florida, and Rev. James McLaughlin of the Wayman Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church in Houston, Texas, are using Scientology's social programs, such as "The Way to Happiness" and "Narconon," to address issues like crime, addiction, and poverty in their communities. While some critics have raised concerns about the church's aggressive recruiting and rigid theology, the pastors argue that they are not embracing Scientology's religious beliefs, but rather using its practical tools to augment their Christian teachings. The article notes that the church has been diversifying its outreach efforts to include other religions and ethnic groups, and that some pastors have found ways to incorporate Scientology's teachings into their sermons without contradicting their Christian beliefs.

A car bomb attack in Algeria has killed 3 people and injured 23, according to the Algerian Press Service. The attack occurred near an office housing judicial police in the city of Thenia, about 50 km east of Algiers. The blast destroyed about 20 houses and a commission has been appointed to help the victims. Islamic extremists in Algeria and other North African countries have carried out several attacks in recent years, including a bombing last year that killed at least 24 people and wounded over 220 at the prime minister's headquarters and a police base in Algiers. Al Qaeda has claimed responsibility for some of these attacks.

Michael Vick, the suspended NFL quarterback, has been ordered by a federal judge to adhere to tightened restrictions after testing positive for marijuana use. Vick must participate in substance abuse therapy and mental health counseling, and will be electronically monitored between 10pm and 6am. He must also comply with random drug testing and a remote alcohol testing system. These conditions will apply until Vick's sentencing on December 10. Vick faces a possible prison term of 12-18 months after pleading guilty to federal conspiracy charges related to dogfighting on his property in Virginia.

Former Beatles Paul McCartney and Ringo Starr were interviewed on CNN's "Larry King Live" to discuss the 40th anniversary of the band's breakup and the Cirque du Soleil show "Love," which uses the Beatles' music. The pair were relaxed and joked frequently, with Starr saying they were "nothing" before joining the band and McCartney retorting that they were good. They discussed the impact of their music and how it has stood the test of time, with McCartney noting that their music has gotten brighter and shinier with age. They also talked about the remixing of their music in 5.1 surround sound and how it has made their songs sound more clear and powerful. The widows of John Lennon and George Harrison were also present and discussed their husbands' involvement in the project before their deaths.

According to the article, three Palestinians, including two sick children, have died recently while waiting for resettlement from Iraq at the Al Waleed refugee camp along the Syrian border. The UNHCR has appealed for the resettlement of "vulnerable and sick" children in the camp, where about 2,000 Palestinian refugees are stranded and face difficult living conditions. Seven people, including three children, have died at the camp since refugees began arriving in March 2006. The UNHCR has helped resettle one family of eight with sick children to Norway last August and is working to identify other medical cases for resettlement. The agency has sought solutions for the whole group since last year and has received positive indications from Sudan and Chile.

A Japanese balloonist, Michio Kanda, has gone missing while flying from Japan to the west coast of the United States. He was last heard from via satellite phone at 9am Alaska time on Thursday, but missed three subsequent scheduled calls. The US Coast Guard has launched searches using planes and cutters, but the balloonist is still missing. Kanda is equipped with provisions and a survival suit, and holds the world record for the longest-duration balloon flight.

The Democratic presidential candidates, Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama, will face off in a debate on Thursday night at the Kodak Theatre in Los Angeles. The debate, sponsored by CNN, the Los Angeles Times, and Politico, will start at 8pm ET and will be moderated by Wolf Blitzer. This will be the first debate since Obama's convincing victory in South Carolina and Clinton's win in the Florida primary. The economy is expected to be a major topic of discussion, as both candidates look to appeal to supporters of John Edwards and his brand of economic populism. Obama has been leading Clinton in the number of pledged delegates, but Clinton has the edge when superdelegates are factored in. The debate comes after Obama raised $32 million in January from roughly 170,000 new donors, which will allow him to expand his television ad buys. Mike Gravel, the other remaining Democratic presidential candidate, was not invited to participate in the debate as he did not meet certain criteria, including support in national polls.

A car bomb exploded near a U.S. Embassy vehicle in Beirut, Lebanon, killing at least three Lebanese bystanders and injuring 21 others, including an American citizen. The driver and passenger of the embassy vehicle were Lebanese security personnel and suffered minor injuries. The U.S. State Department condemned the attack and expressed condolences to the families of the victims. The explosion occurred during a major political crisis in Lebanon, which has been without a president for nearly eight weeks. This is the latest in a series of attacks against pro-Western, anti-Syrian targets in Beirut.

This article from Mental Floss highlights eight unusual fan stories from various sports and events. Here's a summary of each story:

1. Bobby Murcer's Biggest Fan: In 1977, Bobby Murcer, a former New York Yankee, promised a terminally ill fan named Scott Crull that he would hit a home run for him. That night, Murcer hit two home runs, but the fan passed away shortly after. The story gained national attention and highlights the emotional connection between athletes and their fans.
2. The Good Luck Charmers: The Detroit Red Wings have a strange tradition of throwing an octopus onto the ice before games, which is believed to bring them good luck. The tradition started in 1952 and has continued to this day, despite objections from PETA.
3. The John 3:16 Guy: Rollen Stewart, also known as "Rainbow Man," became a fixture at major sporting events in the 1970s and 80s with his John 3:16 signs. He was a born-again Christian and brought his message to various events, including the World Series, Super Bowl, Olympics, and World Cup.
4. The All-Star Heckler: Robin Ficker was a Maryland lawyer and Washington Bullets fan who became the NBA's most prominent heckler. He would loudly disrupt games with his antics, including reading excerpts from a sex-laden autobiography by Phil Jackson.
5. Kim Jong-il: The Supreme Commander of the Korean People's Army is a hoops junkie and has a video library of every Michael Jordan game.
6. David Letterman's Stalker: Margaret Ray was a frequent trespasser on David Letterman's estate and was arrested for stealing his Porsche in 1988. She was later found to have schizophrenia and committed suicide in 1998.
7. Joe from Saddle River: Joe Benigno is a die-hard Jets, Mets, and Rangers fan who became a frequent caller to WFAN, New York's all-sports radio station. He won a contest to guest-host his own show and held the position for almost a decade.
8. Steffi Graf's Biggest Fanatic: Gunter Parche stabbed Monica Seles during a 1993 match in one of the most disturbing incidents in sports history. He was ordered to attend mandatory counseling and received a two-year suspended sentence.
